    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-12-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-12-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="495"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d495">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/559.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Mexican Ambassador</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-12-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 19, 1910</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 367.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                    receipt of your excellency’s note, No. 422, of the 10th instant, transmitting
                    clippings <pb facs="0460" n="378" xml:id="pg_378"/> from the San Antonio Light
                    and Gazette, of the 20th and 21st ultimo, respectively, which, you state, show
                    the character of the acts of Francisco I. Madero.</p>
                <p>In reply I have the honor to state that a copy of your excellency’s note,
                    together with its inclosures, has been sent to the Attorney General for his
                    information.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
